      "problemBody": "<p>Continental climate means sharp seasonal contrasts. In winter, the air is dry outdoors and even drier indoors thanks to central heating. That combination increases TEWL, or transepidermal water loss, which is a fancy way of saying your skin loses water faster than it would like. The result is tightness, roughness and that “nothing sits well” feeling.</p><p>Now add city air, particles and hard water. Your barrier has to work harder just to stay stable. Research on skin barrier function keeps pointing to the same thing: over-cleansing and over-exfoliating can push already stressed skin further into irritation. The mainstream habit of treating skin like a surface to be stripped clean is often the exact wrong move in a dry winter.</p><p>If your skin is living through Vilnius weather, it does not need more punishment. It needs support: gentle cleansing, moisture that stays put, and ingredients that help the skin settle instead of defend itself all day. That is the point where skincare becomes practical, not performative.</p>",
